  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Rational Consumer Choice — The Traditional Assumptions</h2>
    <p>Standard economic theory assumes consumers are <strong>rational</strong>. This means:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>They have <strong>consistent preferences</strong> — they always prefer more of a good over less (ceteris paribus)</li>
      <li>They aim to <strong>maximise utility</strong> (satisfaction) given their budget</li>
      <li>They have <strong>perfect information</strong> about prices, quality, and their own preferences</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Behavioural economics challenges each of these assumptions by drawing on evidence from psychology.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Behavioural Biases</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Bias</th><th>Description</th><th>Example</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Rule of thumb (heuristics)</strong></td>
          <td>Mental shortcuts used to make decisions quickly, especially when information is complex or time is short. Leads to systematic errors.</td>
          <td>Assuming a more expensive wine must be better quality</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Anchoring and framing</strong></td>
          <td>Decisions are influenced by the way information is presented or by an initial reference point ("anchor"), even when irrelevant.</td>
          <td>A product "reduced from $100 to $60" seems a better deal than simply "priced at $60"</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Availability bias</strong></td>
          <td>People overestimate the probability of events that are easy to recall (often because they are vivid or recent).</td>
          <td>Overestimating the risk of plane crashes after seeing news coverage of an accident</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Bounded Concepts</h3>
    <div class="key-terms">
      <div class="key-term-card">
        <div class="term">Bounded rationality</div>
        <div class="definition">Consumers have limited information, cognitive capacity, and time. They make decisions that are "good enough" (satisficing) rather than optimal.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="key-term-card">
        <div class="term">Bounded self-control</div>
        <div class="definition">People fail to act on their own long-term interests — they give in to immediate temptations (present bias). E.g., overeating, not saving enough for retirement.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="key-term-card">
        <div class="term">Bounded selfishness</div>
        <div class="definition">People are not purely self-interested. They care about fairness, others' well-being, and social norms — they sometimes act altruistically.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Behavioural Economics in Action: Nudge Theory</h2>
    <p><strong>Choice architecture</strong> refers to the way choices are designed and presented to decision-makers. Even small changes in how options are framed can significantly affect behaviour without restricting freedom of choice.</p>
    <p><strong>Nudge theory</strong> (Thaler and Sunstein) proposes that governments and organisations can <em>nudge</em> people toward better decisions by designing choice environments carefully.</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Type of choice</th><th>Description</th><th>Example</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Default choice</strong></td>
          <td>People are automatically enrolled in a behaviour and must actively opt out. Takes advantage of inertia and status quo bias.</td>
          <td>Automatic enrolment in pension schemes — employees are in by default and must opt out</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Restricted choice</strong></td>
          <td>Some options are removed from the choice set — usually the most harmful ones.</td>
          <td>Removing unhealthy options from school cafeteria menus</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Mandated choice</strong></td>
          <td>People are required to actively make a choice — they cannot avoid the decision.</td>
          <td>Requiring citizens to state their organ donation preference when renewing a driving licence</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Alternative Business Objectives</h2>
    <p>Standard economic theory assumes firms aim to <strong>maximise profit</strong>. In reality, firms may pursue other objectives:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Objective</th><th>Description</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Profit maximisation</strong></td><td>The traditional assumption — firms produce where MR = MC to maximise the difference between total revenue and total cost</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Corporate social responsibility (CSR)</strong></td><td>Firms consider their impact on employees, communities, and the environment, not just profits</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Market share</strong></td><td>Firms aim to grow their share of the market, even if this reduces short-run profits (e.g., pricing aggressively to gain customers)</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Satisficing</strong></td><td>Firms aim for an acceptable level of profit rather than maximum profit — especially common where ownership and management are separated</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Growth</strong></td><td>Firms aim to expand output, revenue, or assets — managers may prefer growth as it increases their power and remuneration</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="recap">
    <div class="recap-title">Key points to remember</div>
    <ul>
      <li>Rational choice assumes: utility maximisation, consistent preferences, perfect information</li>
      <li>Behavioural biases: rule of thumb, anchoring/framing, availability</li>
      <li>Bounded rationality: limited info and cognitive capacity</li>
      <li>Bounded self-control: short-term temptations override long-term goals</li>
      <li>Nudge: guide behaviour through choice architecture without coercion</li>
      <li>Default choices exploit inertia; restricted choices remove harmful options</li>
      <li>Firms may pursue CSR, market share, satisficing, or growth — not just profit</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="tab-content" id="practice-2-4">
  <div class="callout remember">
    <div class="callout-title">Note</div>
    <p>Practice questions are pending teacher review.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="exercises">
    <div class="exercises-title">Practice Questions <span class="hl-badge">HL</span></div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">1. Explain how "anchoring and framing" challenges the assumption of rational consumer behaviour. Use an example.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          Rational consumers should make decisions based on objective information alone. Anchoring and framing shows this is not the case: the way information is presented (the frame) or an initial reference point (the anchor) affects choices even when irrelevant. For example, a product labelled "was $120, now $80" is perceived as better value than one simply priced at $80, even though the final price is identical. The original price acts as an anchor, making $80 seem cheap by comparison. Rational consumers would ignore this irrelevant information.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">2. Distinguish between "default choice" and "mandated choice" as forms of choice architecture. Give one example of each in a real-world policy context.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          A <strong>default choice</strong> automatically enrols people in an option; they must actively opt out to change it. For example, automatically enrolling employees in a workplace pension scheme — participation rates rise significantly because most people do not bother to opt out. A <strong>mandated choice</strong> requires people to actively make a decision — neither yes nor no is assumed. For example, requiring all adults to state their organ donation preference when applying for a driving licence forces a deliberate choice rather than passive non-participation.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="exercise">
      <div class="exercise-q">3. Explain why firms might pursue "satisficing" rather than profit maximisation.</div>
      <details class="answer">
        <summary>Show answer</summary>
        <div class="answer-content">
          Satisficing occurs when firms aim for an acceptable or "good enough" level of profit rather than the maximum possible. This is most likely when ownership and management are separated (the principal-agent problem) — managers may pursue their own objectives (e.g., large budgets, easy working conditions, avoiding risk) rather than maximising shareholder returns. Finding the true profit-maximising output also requires perfect knowledge of costs and revenues, which firms rarely have. Satisficing therefore reflects bounded rationality at the firm level.
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

